Depending on choice of difficulty, each puzzle can be completed in 5-15 minutes and calls for a mix of word knowledge and deductive reasoning skills. Since its announcement last December, the Unolingo app has enjoyed over 160,000 downloads and our users have completed almost 2 million puzzles.  Appealing to all ages, over 75% of our reviews are 5-stars, and many report Unolingo to be their favorite app.  One of our reviewers offered the following summation; “It is like crosswords and Sudoku had a baby”.  Unolingo is available on all Apple and Android devices including NOOK and Kindle Fire.  The app is available free with 20 starter puzzles and additional puzzles can be purchased in packs of 20 ($.99) or in full Series of 160 ($4.99).   In July, our app was profiled by Amazon as the “Free App of the Day” and we are scheduled for a similar promotion in Europe in November.  We are also in talks with a major media company about book rights and possible syndication of the puzzle.   Unolingo is building a worldwide following and rapidly establishing itself as “The Next Great Puzzle”.   Please visit our website at www.unolingo.com.   Thank you for your consideration. Ian Mailing Managing Director Equazi Enterprises 248-932-3900

Description: The 1772 Foundation works to ensure the safe passage of our historic assets to future generations.
Headquarters Regions: Greater New York Area, East Coast, Northeastern US
Full Description: Preserving American Historical Treasures The 1772 Foundation was named in honor of its first restoration project, Liberty Hall in Union, New Jersey. Built in 1772 by William Livingston, New Jersey’s first elected governor, the residence was home to generations of the Livingston and Kean families, including Stewart Barney Kean, who founded the 1772 Foundation in 1984. Liberty Hall has since been converted into a museum and the Foundation, thanks to Mr. Kean, continues to provide ongoing support for it and many others like it across the country. Upon Mr. Kean's death, in 2002, the Foundation grew from a $2.1 million private foundation to one with over $80 million in assets. In the twenty years since then, the foundation has granted more than $50 million for historic preservation work throughout the United States. After learning of the Kean Family's ties to slavery, the 1772 Foundation has committed to increased funding to racial justice and African American history funding.
